            </pg-code>
          <statement>
            <p>
              In business, we use the equation
              <me>
                P(u) = R(u) - C(u)
              </me>
              where <m>P(u)</m> is the profit you make from selling <m>u</m> tons of some product,
              after you pay expenses.
              The function <m>R(u)</m> represents the revenue from selling the product,
              and <m>C(u)</m> represents the cost you must pay to manufacture the product.
            </p>

            <p>
              The graph below shows the <em>cost</em> and <em>revenue</em>
              functions, where the input,
              <m>u</m>, is the number of tons of the product sold.
            </p>

            <p>
              <var name="$ggb" data="pgml"/>
            </p>

            <p>
              The vertical intercept of the Cost function is at <m>(0, 100)</m>.
              Click and drag this point along the Cost curve <m>y = C(u)</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
              This will move points on the graphs of the Revenue and Profit functions.
            </p>

            <p>
              Notice that the height of the point <m>P(u)</m> is equal to the difference in the heights of points on the <m>R(u)</m> and <m>C(u)</m> graphs.
            </p>

            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Move the point along the graph of <m>C(u)</m> until the profit is zero.
                    At approximately how many tons will the profit be zero (give your answer to the nearest whole number)?
                    Note:
                    This value is called the <em>break even</em> point,
                    after which the business begins to make actual profit.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    <var name="$profitIsZero" width="5" /> tons
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Now click the box to show the graph of <m>P(u)</m>.
                    Notice that it begins with negative outputs,
                    increasing to the break even point,
                    and becoming positive thereafter.
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    <ul>
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          If <m>C(</m><var name="$u1" /><m>) = </m><var name="$c1" /> and <m>R(</m><var name="$u1" /><m>) = </m><var name="$r1" />, then what is <m>P(</m><var name="$u1" /><m>)</m>?
                        </p>

                        <p>
                          Answer:
                          <var name="$p1" width="10" />
                        </p>
                      </li>

                      <li>
                        <p>
                          If it costs <var name="$c2" /> thousand dollars to produce <var name="$u2" /> tons,
                          and the revenue is <var name="$r2" /> thousand dollars,
                          then what is <m>P(</m><var name="$u2" /><m>)</m>?
                        </p>

                        <p>
                          Answer:
                          <var name="$p2" width="10" />
                        </p>
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              <ol label="a">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The profit should be <m>0</m> when <m>R(u)</m> and <m>C(u)</m> are equal.
                    Find this on the graph.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Remember the definition of the function:
                    <m>P(u) = R(u) - C(u)</m>
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    So:
                    <m>P(<var name="$u1" />) \approx R(<var name="$u1" />) - C(<var name="$u1" />)</m>
                  </p>

                  <p>
                    Find this on the graph.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>P(<var name="$u2" />) \approx R(<var name="$u2" />) - C(<var name="$u2" />)</m>
