    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          As a business owner,
          you know the value in giving your customers a good deal,
          especially when they buy a lot from you.
        </p>

        <p>
          This month at your pet supply store,
          you decide to run the following special on your most popular cat food.
        </p>

        <p>
          The retail price for one container of the food is <m>\$24</m>,
          but if a customer orders two of them,
          you will reduce the unit price by <m>\$0{.}25</m>,
          so they would each cost only <m>\$23{.}75</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          If a customer orders three containers,
          the unit cost would be reduced another <m>\$0{.}25</m>,
          so they would each cost only <m>\$23{.}50</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Thus, as the number of containers increases,
          the cost of each one will decrease.
        </p>

        <p>
          <ol label="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Write a formula for the unit cost, <m>C(x)</m>,
                of each container when the customer orders <m>x</m> containers.
                Note that this is a <em>linear</em> function of <m>x</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                If a customer ordered <m>6</m> containers,
                we could evaluate <m>C(6)</m> to find how much they would be charged for each container.
                How much would they pay in total for all six containers?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                If a customer ordered <m>x</m> containers,
                how much would they pay in total for all the containers?
                Let <m>T(x)</m> represent the total they would pay for <m>x</m> containers.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The Cost function is linear,
          beginning at <m>24</m> when <m>x = 1</m>,
          and with a slope of <m>-0.25</m>.
          So, the function can be written as:
          <md>
            <mrow>C(x) \amp= 24 - 0.25(x-1)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 24.25 - 0.25x</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If a customer ordered <m>6</m> containers, the unit cost would be:
          <md>
            <mrow>C(6) \amp= 24.25 - 0.25(6)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 22.75</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          You would charge <m>\$22{.}75</m> for each container,
          so the customer would pay <m>6(22.75) = </m> <m>\$136{.}50</m> in total.
        </p>
      </solution>
      <solution>
        <p>
          In general, if a customer ordered <m>x</m> containers,
          then they would have to pay the unit cost (given by the function <m>C(x)</m>) multiplied by the number of containers they ordered
          (which is just <m>x</m>).
        </p>

        <p>
          Therefore, the customer's total cost for ordering <m>x</m> containers is a new function:
          <md>
            <mrow>T(x) \amp= x \cdot C(x)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= x(24.25 - 0.25x)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 24.25x - 0.25x^2</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Graphing Combinations</title>
      <p>
        Because there are an infinite number of ways to combine two functions,
        there is no straightforward way to describe all possible graphs we may see as a result.
        However, one thing <em>is</em> true for any function combination we may create:
        <em>We are just doing arithmetic on the outputs of the original functions.</em>
      </p>

      <p>
        This means that for a combination such as
        <me>
          W(x) = \left(g(x)+h(x)\right)^3 + 4g(x)
        </me>
        in order to evaluate a particular value such as <m>W(12)</m>,
        the number <m>12</m> must at least be in the domains of both functions <m>g</m> and <m>h</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        If <m>g(12) = 3</m> and <m>h(12) = 2</m>,
        then <m>W(x)</m> would be:
        <me>
          (3+2)^3 + 4(3) = 137
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        In the next exercise,
        you will see four different combinations of the functions
        <m>f(x) = x-1</m> and <m>g(x) = 2-x</m>.
      </p>

      <exercise>
        <webwork>

            <pg-code>
              $ggb = q![@MODES(HTML=&gt;'&lt;iframe scrolling="no" src="https://www.geogebra.org/material/iframe/id/tAcMxrpj/width/411/height/410/border/888888/smb/false/stb/false/stbh/false/ai/false/asb/false/sri/true/rc/false/ld/false/sdz/false/ctl/false" width="411px" height="410px" style="border:0px;"&gt; &lt;/iframe&gt;', TeX =&gt;"A GeoGebra applet.", PTX =&gt;"A GeoGebra applet.");@]*!;
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The graphs of <m>f(x) = x - 1</m> and <m>g(x) = 2 - x</m> are shown below.
              </p>

              <p>
                Before manipulating the graph,
                try to make the predictions that follow.
              </p>

              <p>
                <var name="$ggb" data="pgml"/>
              </p>

              <p>
                <ol label="a">
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>J(x) = f(x) + g(x)</m>,
                      can you predict the value of <m>J(2)</m>?
                    </p>

                    <p>
                      Now click the checkbox to check your answer.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>K(x) = g(x) - f(x)</m>,
                      can you predict the value of <m>K(2)</m>?
                    </p>

                    <p>
                      Now click the checkbox to check your answer.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>L(x) = f(x)g(x)</m>, can you predict the value of <m>L(2)</m>?
                    </p>

                    <p>
                      Now click the checkbox to check your answer.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>M(x) = f(x)/g(x)</m>, can you predict the value of <m>M(2)</m>?
                    </p>

                    <p>
                      Now click the checkbox to check your answer.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
              <p>
                <ol label="a">
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Notice that <m>J(2)</m> is equal to <m>1</m>,
                      because <m>f(2) = 1</m> and
                      <m>g(2) = 0</m>, and <m>1 + 0 = 1</m>.
                      However, clicking to show the graph of
                      <m>y = J(x)</m> shows that its output is
                      <em>always</em> equal to <m>1</m>.
                      In order to see why this is,
                      just remember that <m>f(x) = x - 1</m> and <m>g(x) = 2 - x</m>.
                      Now simplify the expression <m>f(x) + g(x) = (x - 1) + (2 - x)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Next, see that <m>K(2)</m> is equal to <m>-1</m> because <m>0 - 1 = -1</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      For <m>L(2)</m>, the output is <m>0</m> because <m>-1(0) = 0</m>.
                      Notice the shape of this graph -- it is a <em>parabola</em>,
                      which is the result of multiplying two linear functions.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Finally, the value of <m>M(2)</m> is <em>undefined</em>,
                      because <m>g(2) = 0</m>, and we cannot divide anything by zero.
                      So, the combination <m>f(x)/g(x)</m> makes sense only when the output for <m>g(x)</m> is not zero.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </hint>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>
