            <statement>
              <p>The total cost function, <m>T(x)</m>, may be thought of as a combination of two different functions, <m>C(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m>.</p>
              <p>We already determined the unit cost function, <m>C(x)</m>, in the last problem. Restate it below:</p>
              <p><m>C(x) = </m><var name="$unitCost" width="15" /></p>
              <p>The other function is a simple, but important part of the total cost.</p>
              <p>If we want to charge someone for a purchase, we need the unit cost and the quantity being purchased. Let our second function be the quantity, <m>Q(x)</m>, of items being purchased.</p>
              <p>What is the quantity being purchased in general? This is easier than you think.</p>
              <p>Answer:  <m>Q(x) = </m><var name="$sold" width="15" /></p>
              <p>Finally, we combine these to make the total cost function, <m>T(x)</m>:</p>
              <p><m>T(x) = C(x)\cdot Q(x) = </m><var name="$totalCost" width="15" /></p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
              <p>The function <m>Q(x)</m> is supposed to find the quantity being purchased. However, you should remember that the input for the function, <m>x</m>, is also the quantity being purchased.</p>
              <p>So, the input and output for the function are both equal.</p>
            </hint>
            <solution>
              <p><ol>
                <li><p>The unit cost function is:  <m>C(x) = </m><var name="$unitCost" /></p></li>
                <li><p>The quantity function is:  <m>Q(x) = </m><var name="$sold" /></p></li>
                <li><p>The total cost function is:  <m>T(x) = </m><var name="$totalCost" /></p></li>
              </ol></p>
            </solution>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
      -->
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Combinations vs. Composition</title>
      <p>
        It may have occurred to you that function combinations look very much like composite functions.
        For example, the expression
        <me>
          \left(f(x)\right)^2 + 3f(x)
        </me>
        is a combination of just the function <m>f(x)</m>.
        However, it may also be thought of as the
        <em>composition</em> <m>g(f(x))</m>,
        where <m>g(x) = x^2 + 3x</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        In general, this is true:
        A composite function is really just a
        <q>combination of itself</q>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Now you would be justified to ask:
        If combinations and compositions are so similar,
        why do we have two different names for them?
        The answer is that, while similar,
        they represent different things we may do with function outputs,
        especially in a real context.
        Here is an example:
      </p>

      <example>
        <statement>
          <p>
            As the temperature drops, so does the speed of sound.
            The function
            <me>
              v = f(T) = 740.4 + 1.34T
            </me>
            models the speed of sound
            (in miles-per-hour)
            when the temperature is <m>T</m> degrees Celsius.
          </p>

          <p>
            On a particular day between <m>6{:}00</m> <pm/> and midnight,
            suppose the temperature outside is modeled by the function
            <me>
              T = g(h) = 24 - 3h
            </me>
            where <m>h</m> is the number of hours after <m>6{:}00</m> <pm/>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Now, we certainly could create both combinations and compositions using the functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>,
            but what would actually makes sense?
          </p>

          <p>
            Since we know that <m>g</m> changes <em>hours</em>
            into <em>degrees Celsius</em>,
            and <m>f</m> changes <em>degrees Celsius</em> into
            <em>miles-per-hour</em>,
            it seems natural to use the composition
            <me>
              f(g(h)) = 740.4+1.34(24-3h)
            </me>
            to turn <em>hours</em> into <em>miles-per-hour</em>.
          </p>

          <p>
            It would not be sensible to make a combination of the functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>,
            because they do not use the same input variable.
            We would have to use the same input value
            (with the same units)
            into both functions, but this cannot be.
          </p>

          <p>
            However, outside of any context,
            the functions <m>f(x) = 740.4 + 1.34x</m> and
            <m>g(x) = 24 - 3x</m> could be combined in any variety of ways.
            These combinations, however,
            would have no applicable meaning in the given story about temperature and the speed of sound.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </subsection>

